<glossary>

<definition id="fs-id1356632">
<term>simple interest</term>
<meaning id="fs-id1166490832230">If an amount of money, <m:math><m:mi>P</m:mi></m:math>, the principal, is invested for a period of <m:math><m:mi>t</m:mi></m:math> years at an annual interest rate <m:math><m:mi>r</m:mi></m:math>, the amount of interest, <m:math><m:mi>I</m:mi></m:math>, earned is <m:math><m:mi>I</m:mi><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>P</m:mi><m:mi>r</m:mi><m:mi>t</m:mi></m:math>. Interest earned according to this formula is called simple interest.</meaning>
</definition>
</glossary>
